"1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1266–Male":"1266–Deceased","1288":"1288","1266":"1266","1330":"1330","1290":"1290","Naas, Kildare, Leinster, Ireland ":"Naas, County Kildare, Ireland","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Loundres","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Lowndes  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lowndes","meanings":["English: variant of   Lown  ."]}]},{"name":"Knight","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: status or occupational name from Middle English <i>knight</i> ‘retainer, attendant’ (Old English <i>cniht</i> ‘boy, youth, lad)’. The specialized feudal sense ‘a high-ranking tenant bound to serve his lord as a mounted soldier’ is not known to have ever given rise to the surname, although it is not out of the question that it may occasionally have been used as a nickname, perhaps for someone who played the part of an armed knight in a local pageant.","Irish: sometimes adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac an Ridire</b> ‘son of the knight’. See also   McKnight  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Knights","meanings":["English (East Anglia): variant of   Knight  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"McKnight","meanings":["Irish: part translation of Gaelic <b>Mac an Ridire</b> ‘son of the horseman (Gaelic <i>ridire</i>)’, formerly Anglicized <i>McRuddery</i>.","Scottish (Dumfriesshire and Galloway) and Irish (Ulster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Neachtain</b>, which is usually Anglicized as   McNaughton  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William Loundres Knight was born in 1288, in England, United Kingdom as the son of William de Loundres. He had at least 1 son with Lady Emma De Loundres."},"et":{"1288–":"1288–Surnud","1288–Male":"1288–Surnud","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1266–Male":"1266–Surnud","1288":"1288","1266":"1266","1330":"1330","1290":"1290","Naas, Kildare, Leinster, Ireland ":"Naas, County Kildare, Iirimaa","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1288–":"1288–Kuollut","1288–Male":"1288–Kuollut","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1266–Male":"1266–Kuollut","1288":"1288","1266":"1266","1330":"1330","1290":"1290","Naas, Kildare, Leinster, Ireland ":"Naas, County Kildare, Irlanti","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1288–":"1288–Décédé","1288–Male":"1288–Décédé","1290–Female":"1290–Décédée","1330–Male":"1330–Décédé","1266–Male":"1266–Décédé","1288":"1288","1266":"1266","1330":"1330","1290":"1290","Naas, Kildare, Leinster, Ireland ":"Naas, County Kildare, Irlande","England, United Kingdom":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Sir William Loundres Knight est né en 1288, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de William de Loundres. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Lady Emma De Loundres."},"de":{"1288–":"1288–Verstorben","1288–Male":"1288–Verstorben","1290–Female":"1290–Verstorben","1330–Male":"1330–Verstorben","1266–Male":"1266–Verstorben","1288":"1288","1266":"1266","1330":"1330","1290":"1290","Naas, Kildare, Leinster, Ireland ":"Naas, County Kildare, I